<paragraph id="666036ACFF97FF96BDF2BE4B167E8CB2" blockId="96.[151,1436,730,910]" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis id="54ABEABEFF97FF96BDF2BE4B15B18C7C" box="[207,457,808,832]" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Diagnostic characters</emphasis>
: The presence of circular single pars ventralis (
<figureCitation id="FEE42A29FF97FF96BEE2BE4A10128C7C" box="[991,1130,808,832]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="100.[151,250,1680,1703]" captionTargetBox="[288,1289,164,1665]" captionTargetId="figure-109@100.[240,1374,153,1665]" captionTargetPageId="100" captionText="FIGURE 33. Allocladius spp., male hypopygium; A, D, G, dorsal aspect; B, E, F, pars ventralis; C, F, I, ventral aspect. A–C. A. neobilobulatus (Paggi). D–F. A. globosus Andersen, Saether et Mendes.; G–I. A. quadrus Andersen, Saether et Mendes. (From Andersen et al. 2010.)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5288353" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5288353/files/figure.png" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Fig. 33 D–F</figureCitation>
) about as long as wide and with setae together with the absence of an accessory lobe of the inferior volsella will separate the species from other species with pars ventralis.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="666036ACFF97FF96BDAABEA617528CE0" blockId="96.[151,810,964,988]" box="[151,810,964,988]" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">
The male is described in detail in Andersen 
<emphasis id="54ABEABEFF97FF96BF49BEA716D38CE0" box="[628,683,964,988]" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">et al.</emphasis>
(2010: 11).
</paragraph>
